[1]
Date: Sun, 03 Oct 1999 20:48:55 -0700
From: DJR <djr@onlinemac.com>

As an allied health worker who deals with various diseases weekly, and
observes the impact of such on individuals, children, families, contacts,
medical personnel, etc., I suggest we poll the patients and ask them if
they believe the spread of disease which has cost them the lives and health
of people they know and love is a "good" thing. This may be a good abstract
thesis, but I'm trying to save or heal my patients, in accordance with my
oath, and I cannot subscribe to it from my point of view.
--
David J. Rogers
Director, Wilderness Medical Consultants
<djr@onlinemac.com>
[I think David -- & some other readers who wrote in similar vein -- have
missed the point. The original post asked whether "spread ... might be a
"good thing" ... *if* it means that the countries who can afford to look
(for), identify and implement cost-effective solutions are given an
incentive to do so?" Meaning that developed countries are not going to
research exotic diseases unless & until they are infected by them - Mod.JW]
