[2]
Mon, 4 Oct 1999 19:51:24 -0400 (EDT)
From: d1r1corr@aol.com

Should Ebola rear her ugly head along say, the Mississippi River here in the
USA, what are the odds that the drug manufacturers would come up with an
effective treatment or a vaccine?
Frankly, though, don't you believe that all treatment of disease goes
against nature and that survival of the fittest no longer applies? This may
be the real reason for the rampant transmission of deadly disease. The
"strong" are no longer the only survivors -- antibiotics and surgery make it
possible for those who would have died to live and reproduce more of their
kind with defective genes. The bacteria are fighting back though and
finding ways to resist the antibiotics that science has provided.
So with these perspectives, does science "owe" it to us to find new cures or
[are] some of the "cures" actually killing us? If science can find new
cures, we should be appreciative of the efforts made by the tireless
individuals trying to do so. They don't "owe" us anything. Appreciate what
there is and take it with a grain of salt.

R. Corr
Bryan, Texas, USA
d1r1corr@aol.com
