[6]
Date: Wed, 6 Oct 1999 09:56:26 -0700
From: "Bowers, Mark H. (SFMH)" <MBowers@chw.edu>

Recent data that show substantial reductions in the perinatal transmission
of HIV following 2 doses of nevirapine has provided even greater hope for
people in "third
world countries" than current testing of HIV vaccine candidates.
Both nevirapine, a non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor, and the
current subunit HIV vaccine candidates were researched and developed in
Western Europe and the United States. Both are being tested (and apparently
discounted) in third world nations. The vast majority of currently approved
therapies for HIV disease remain well beyond the means of the southeast
Asian and African nations that are hardest hit by the epidemic, and beyond
the means of poor people in the first world. However, the case could still
be made that these 2 relatively inexpensive medications will save lives and
ease misery in the third world as well as in the first.
--
Mark Bowers, MS
HIVCare Clinical Research Center
St. Francis Memorial Hospital
San Francisco, CA 94109
<MBowers@chw.edu>
[Doesn´t this prove Peter´s case? Does anybody think these drugs would have
been developed if HIV had never spread to developed countries? - Mod.JW]
